## Data Schema

### Beneficiaries (`beneficiaries.csv`)
| Column | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| beneficiary_id | string | Unique ID (BEN0001…) |
| name | string | Placeholder name |
| age | int | Age (10–60), ~2% nulls injected |
| gender | string | Male / Female / Other |
| state | string | One of 12 Indian states |
| program | string | One of 8 programmes |
| category | string | Education / Health / Livelihood / Environment |
| enrollment_date | datetime | Monthly, Apr 2024 – Mar 2025 |
| completion_status | string | Enrolled / Completed / Dropped |
| satisfaction_score | float | 3.0–5.0, ~1% nulls injected |

### Donations (`donations.csv`)
| Column | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| donation_id | string | Unique ID (DON0001…) |
| donor_name | string | Placeholder name |
| source | string | Individual / CSR / Government / Events / Online |
| amount | float | ₹500–₹5L (Individual), ₹50K–₹2L (CSR), ₹1L–₹5L (Govt) |
| date | datetime | Daily, Apr 2024 – Mar 2025 |
| last_donation_date | datetime | date + 0–90 days, capped at Mar 2025 |
| frequency | int | 1–11 donations per donor |
| month | Period[M] | Monthly period |
| quarter | Period[Q] | Quarterly period |
| program_allocated | string | Programme the donation is assigned to |
| is_repeat_donor | bool | 62% True |

### Volunteers (`volunteers.csv`)
| Column | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| volunteer_id | string | Unique ID (VOL0001…) |
| name | string | Placeholder name |
| age | int | 18–55 |
| gender | string | Male / Female / Other |
| state | string | One of 12 Indian states |
| program_assigned | string | One of 8 programmes |
| hours_contributed | float | 10–300 hours |
| join_year | int | 2020–2025 (weighted toward recent years) |
| retention_status | string | Active (74%) / Inactive (26%) |
| skills | string | Teaching / Tech / Medical / Admin / Field Work |

---

## Methodology

**Seed:** `numpy.random.seed(42)` — all data is fully reproducible across runs.

**Data Quality Nulls:** ~2% nulls are deliberately injected into `satisfaction_score` and `age` in the beneficiary dataset to demonstrate the data quality audit feature.

**RFM Binning:** Quintile-based (`pd.qcut`) with rank-based tie-breaking for frequency to avoid empty bin errors on low-cardinality columns.

**Forecasting:** First-degree polynomial (`numpy.polyfit` with deg=1) fitted on 12 monthly observations. Predictions are floored at zero. This is intentionally simple — the model is demonstrative, not production-grade.

**Impact Score Normalisation:** Min-max normalisation applied independently per metric before weighting so no single metric dominates due to scale differences.

---

## Output Files

| File | Description |
|---|---|
| `nayepankh_report.html` | Self-contained interactive report (open in any browser) |
| `beneficiaries.csv` | 500-row beneficiary export |
| `donations.csv` | 300-row donation export |
| `volunteers.csv` | 200-row volunteer export |

The HTML report embeds Plotly via CDN. An internet connection is required to render the charts when opening the file.

---

## Customisation

**Change dataset size:** Pass different `n` values to the generator functions in `main()`.

**Change date range:** Edit the `pd.date_range` start/end strings in `generate_donation_data` and `generate_beneficiary_data`.

**Adjust Impact Score weights:** Modify the five multipliers in `compute_impact_scores()` — they must sum to 100.

**Add a new programme:** Append to the `PROGRAMS` list and add a corresponding entry to `CATEGORIES`. All downstream calculations will pick it up automatically.

**Change RFM segment thresholds:** Edit the score boundaries in the `segment()` function inside `compute_rfm()`.

**Save report to a custom path:**
```python
generate_html_report(kpis, ben_df, don_df, vol_df, output_path="my_report.html")
```

